# lxz, environment sandbox shortcuts with LXD

Once upon a time in a galaxy far, far away...

I needed a sandbox where I can install packages for a project without polluting my distro. LXD
containers are basically thin VMs — full OS, persistent by default, disposable when you're done.

### Why LXD, not Docker

Docker is great for reproducible stuff, but I don't need reproducible. I want a draft where
everything persists, but easy to toss away. Also, GUI apps in Docker feel clunky.

### What it does

On first run, creates a base container with:

- X11 forwarding (GPU accelerated, NVIDIA only for now)
- A chosen host directory mounted with read/write
- Passwordless SSH access
- Docker support (nesting enabled)

Every new container is cloned from this base. Base image is Ubuntu Noble.

### Usage

`lxz help`

Examples:

- `lxz cd myproject` — into container, creates it if it doesn't exist
- `lxz ip myproject` — get IP for VSCode SSH

### Install

```sh
curl -L https://raw.githubusercontent.com/haoadoreorange/lxz/main/install.sh | sh `[install directory]`
```

May install

- `lxd` on your system
- <https://github.com/niieani/bash-oo-framework>

### Limitations

All `lxc` commands run with sudo — I don't add my user to the `lxd` group since it's
[root-equivalent](https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/LXD#Configure_LXD).

### Security

Convenience over hardening. Read the script if that matters to you. PRs welcome.
